12/Mar/2021 (updated 07 junio, 2021)

Abstract

This document analyses the reliability and scheduling performance of the self-developed library NativeScript Task Dispatcher (NTD) in a series of Android-based mobile devices as part of the SyMptOMS project. The main outcome of the paper is the NTD library. This notebook focuses on the results of the Experiment 1 (simple task scheduling), which are Table 1 and Figure 4.

Required libraries and runtime environment description are as follows.

library(tidyverse)
library(kableExtra)
library(here)
library(lubridate)
library(stringr)
library(scales)
library(grid)
library(gridBase)
library(gridExtra)

As reported in the paper, we deployed two applications to run the Experiment 1 (simple task scheduling): 1/ an ad-hoc application written in Java without an alarm watchdog, 2/ a NativeScript application that uses the NTD library. Both applications ran a simple recurrent task – without logic or complex computations to produce a minimal execution overhead – every minute for 2 weeks. We reused the data files generated in April/May 2020, whose file names start with the prefix BA_ corresponds to the ad-hoc application (option 1). The data file names that start with AD_ where created with the NTD-based application (option 2) in February 2021.

1 Data preparation

Raw data files are cleaned and merged together into a single file exp1/data/data_ieeetmc. Total observations: 138653. Key variables, as explained below, are computed too.

  • quantitative (interval)

    • plan_date (POSIXct, POSIXt): task planning time.
    • exec_date (POSIXct, POSIXt): task execution time.
    • step: relative position

  • quantitative (ratio)

    • diff (difftime): difference in seconds between the current and previous execution times.
    • diff_secs (numeric): numeric value of diff.
    • delay (numeric): normalised execution delay in seconds (diff_secs - 60).

  • categorical (nominal)

    • device_id: device identifier
    • device_name: device name
    • device_os: Android OS version
    • scheduler: scheduler type

2.2 Missingness of data

We compute the data loss ratio, i.e. the expected number of task executions against the real one.

Devices A1 and NV with the Ad-hoc scheduler did not end the experiment. The expected number of executions were 20,264 and 20,264, respectively.

2.3 Outliers

We discard 77 out of 138,653 observations whose abs(delay) >= 10 seconds.

2.4 Figure 4 (included in the paper)

Delay distribution per device and type of application. Percentage of missing task executions at the top (lower is better). Devices are sorted from the oldest to the newest version of Android. Green represents ad-hoc application, orange the NTD-based application.
